event: response.output_text.done
data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_0b83d6600b16c6310169e44e38ca048190aeb13d19555c414c","logprobs":[],"output_index":1,"sequence_number":664,"text":"Here’s a purely logic-based explanation of the **Monty Hall 3-door problem** (1 prize, 1 player choice, host opens a goat door, then you may switch).\n\n### Rules (important)\n- You initially choose **one** of 3 doors.\n- The host **knows** where the prize is.\n- The host then opens **one of the two unchosen doors**, but **only if it contains a goat**.\n- Finally, you may **switch** to the remaining unopened door or **stay** with your original.\n\n---\n\n## Step 1: Split by what your first choice actually was\nThere are only two logical possibilities for your initial pick:\n\n### Case 1: You initially picked the prize (probability = 1/3)\n- This happens in **1 out of 3** situations.\n- The host must open a goat among the other two doors.\n- After the host opens one goat, the **only prize** remains on your original door.\n- So:\n  - **If you stay:** you win.\n  - **If you switch:** you lose.\n\n### Case 2: You initially picked a goat (probability = 2/3)\n- This happens in **2 out of 3** situations.\n- Now the prize is behind the **other unchosen door** (the one the host does *not* open).\n- The host again is forced to open a goat, but there’s a key logical fact:\n  - He can’t open the prize door; he must open a goat door.\n- So when he opens one goat door, the **only unopened door left must be the prize**.\n- So:\n  - **If you stay:** you lose.\n  - **If you switch:** you win.\n\n---\n\n## Step 2: Combine the cases\n- **Stay wins only in Case 1** → probability **1/3**\n- **Switch wins only in Case 2** → probability **2/3**\n\nSo:\n- **Switching wins with probability 2/3**\n- **Staying wins with probability 1/3**\n\n---\n\n## Why the common “1/2 and 1/2” intuition fails\nPeople often think: “After one door is opened, two doors remain, so it’s 50/50.”\n\nBut that’s not logically valid because the host’s action is **not random**:\n- He deliberately avoids the prize and always opens a goat.\n- That conditional behavior concentrates probability on the remaining unopened door that you didn’t initially pick.\n\nIn effect, your initial choice had probability:\n- **1/3** to be correct,\n- **2/3** to be wrong,\nand the host’s forced goat-opening preserves that split—switching captures the **2/3 “wrong” mass**."}

event: response.content_part.done
data: {"type":"response.content_part.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_0b83d6600b16c6310169e44e38ca048190aeb13d19555c414c","output_index":1,"part":{"type":"output_text","annotations":[],"logprobs":[],"text":"Here’s a purely logic-based explanation of the **Monty Hall 3-door problem** (1 prize, 1 player choice, host opens a goat door, then you may switch).\n\n### Rules (important)\n- You initially choose **one** of 3 doors.\n- The host **knows** where the prize is.\n- The host then opens **one of the two unchosen doors**, but **only if it contains a goat**.\n- Finally, you may **switch** to the remaining unopened door or **stay** with your original.\n\n---\n\n## Step 1: Split by what your first choice actually was\nThere are only two logical possibilities for your initial pick:\n\n### Case 1: You initially picked the prize (probability = 1/3)\n- This happens in **1 out of 3** situations.\n- The host must open a goat among the other two doors.\n- After the host opens one goat, the **only prize** remains on your original door.\n- So:\n  - **If you stay:** you win.\n  - **If you switch:** you lose.\n\n### Case 2: You initially picked a goat (probability = 2/3)\n- This happens in **2 out of 3** situations.\n- Now the prize is behind the **other unchosen door** (the one the host does *not* open).\n- The host again is forced to open a goat, but there’s a key logical fact:\n  - He can’t open the prize door; he must open a goat door.\n- So when he opens one goat door, the **only unopened door left must be the prize**.\n- So:\n  - **If you stay:** you lose.\n  - **If you switch:** you win.\n\n---\n\n## Step 2: Combine the cases\n- **Stay wins only in Case 1** → probability **1/3**\n- **Switch wins only in Case 2** → probability **2/3**\n\nSo:\n- **Switching wins with probability 2/3**\n- **Staying wins with probability 1/3**\n\n---\n\n## Why the common “1/2 and 1/2” intuition fails\nPeople often think: “After one door is opened, two doors remain, so it’s 50/50.”\n\nBut that’s not logically valid because the host’s action is **not random**:\n- He deliberately avoids the prize and always opens a goat.\n- That conditional behavior concentrates probability on the remaining unopened door that you didn’t initially pick.\n\nIn effect, your initial choice had probability:\n- **1/3** to be correct,\n- **2/3** to be wrong,\nand the host’s forced goat-opening preserves that split—switching captures the **2/3 “wrong” mass**."},"sequence_number":665}

event: response.output_item.done
data: {"type":"response.output_item.done","item":{"id":"msg_0b83d6600b16c6310169e44e38ca048190aeb13d19555c414c","type":"message","status":"completed","content":[{"type":"output_text","annotations":[],"logprobs":[],"text":"Here’s a purely logic-based explanation of the **Monty Hall 3-door problem** (1 prize, 1 player choice, host opens a goat door, then you may switch).\n\n### Rules (important)\n- You initially choose **one** of 3 doors.\n- The host **knows** where the prize is.\n- The host then opens **one of the two unchosen doors**, but **only if it contains a goat**.\n- Finally, you may **switch** to the remaining unopened door or **stay** with your original.\n\n---\n\n## Step 1: Split by what your first choice actually was\nThere are only two logical possibilities for your initial pick:\n\n### Case 1: You initially picked the prize (probability = 1/3)\n- This happens in **1 out of 3** situations.\n- The host must open a goat among the other two doors.\n- After the host opens one goat, the **only prize** remains on your original door.\n- So:\n  - **If you stay:** you win.\n  - **If you switch:** you lose.\n\n### Case 2: You initially picked a goat (probability = 2/3)\n- This happens in **2 out of 3** situations.\n- Now the prize is behind the **other unchosen door** (the one the host does *not* open).\n- The host again is forced to open a goat, but there’s a key logical fact:\n  - He can’t open the prize door; he must open a goat door.\n- So when he opens one goat door, the **only unopened door left must be the prize**.\n- So:\n  - **If you stay:** you lose.\n  - **If you switch:** you win.\n\n---\n\n## Step 2: Combine the cases\n- **Stay wins only in Case 1** → probability **1/3**\n- **Switch wins only in Case 2** → probability **2/3**\n\nSo:\n- **Switching wins with probability 2/3**\n- **Staying wins with probability 1/3**\n\n---\n\n## Why the common “1/2 and 1/2” intuition fails\nPeople often think: “After one door is opened, two doors remain, so it’s 50/50.”\n\nBut that’s not logically valid because the host’s action is **not random**:\n- He deliberately avoids the prize and always opens a goat.\n- That conditional behavior concentrates probability on the remaining unopened door that you didn’t initially pick.\n\nIn effect, your initial choice had probability:\n- **1/3** to be correct,\n- **2/3** to be wrong,\nand the host’s forced goat-opening preserves that split—switching captures the **2/3 “wrong” mass**."}],"phase":"final_answer","role":"assistant"},"output_index":1,"sequence_number":666}

